		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id720654d682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>9:18.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Statements of existing mental, emotional, or physical condition</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>
						<cite.query w-src-number="0287017177" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-8-803" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I04b147b074d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-8-803(3)</cite.query> generally provides an exception to hearsay for a declarant&apos;s statement of a then existing state of mind, emotion, sensation, or physical condition, such as intent, plan, motive, design, mental feeling, pain, and bodily health. <eos/>
						<bos/>
						<cite.query w-src-number="0287017177" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER803" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="I04b147b174d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Fed. R. Evid. 803</cite.query> contains two provisions for declarations of physical condition. <eos/>
						<bos/>
						<cite.query w-src-number="0287017177" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USFRER803" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="I04b147b274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Rule 803(3)</cite.query> is primarily concerned with statements about the declarant&apos;s state of mind but also includes statements of the declarant&apos;s “then existing … physical condition.”<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Historically, Georgia courts have been unwilling to adopt a clear exception for declarations of present bodily condition and symptoms.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7a1995c074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] Nonetheless, statements of present physical condition may be admissible if made under such circumstances as to be equivalent to spontaneous and involuntary exclamations or physical manifestations of pain and suffering[<footnote.reference refid="I7a1995c174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] or if the declarant is dead.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7a1995c274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>However, in order for statements to come in under this exception, the declarant&apos;s state of mind must be a relevant issue in the case. <eos/>
						<bos/>Thus, where a declarant made statements regarding a MARTA accident, they were not admissible under this exception to hearsay since the declarant&apos;s state of mind was not relevant to MARTA&apos;s alleged negligence.[<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<footnote.reference refid="I7a1995c374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
		</section>
		<footnote.block>
			<footnote ID="I7a1995c074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>1</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017177" w-serial-number="1893008110" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I04b195d274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Atlanta St. R. Co. v. Walker, 93 Ga. 462, 21 S.E. 48 (1893)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>Georgia cases have rather broadly used the exception of spontaneous statements of present pain or condition and state that such statements are original evidence. <eos/>
							<bos/>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017177" w-serial-number="1896009665" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I04b20b0274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Broyles v. Prisock, 97 Ga. 643, 25 S.E. 389 (1896)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017177" w-serial-number="1909012498" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I04b2321274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Georgia Ry. &amp; Electric Co. v. Gilleland, 133 Ga. 621, 66 S.E. 944 (1909)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017177" w-serial-number="1912016027" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I04b2321574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Southern Ry. Co. v. Parham, 10 Ga. App. 531, 73 S.E. 763 (1912)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017177" w-serial-number="1952104402" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I04b2321874d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Lassiter v. Poss, 85 Ga. App. 785, 70 S.E.2d 411 (1952)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I7a1995c174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>2</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>See <cite.query w-src-number="0287017177" w-serial-number="1967130287" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I04b2a74274d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">Paulk v. Thomas, 115 Ga. App. 436, 154 S.E.2d 872 (1967)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017177" w-serial-number="1971127986" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I04b2a74574d311eab2f0b920da2605c5">East Point Ford Co. v. Lingerfelt, 123 Ga. App. 520, 181 S.E.2d 713 (1971)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
